solution:
type RequiredKeys<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]-?: {} extends Pick<T, K> ? never : K;
}[keyof T];

class Builder<T, Provided extends keyof T = never> {
  private data: Partial<T> = {};

  set<K extends keyof T>(key: K, value: T[K]): Builder<T, Provided | K> {
    (this.data as any)[key] = value;
    return this as unknown as Builder<T, Provided | K>;
  }

  // The `this` parameter constrains WHO can call build(): only a Builder whose
  // Provided union already includes every RequiredKeys<T> member satisfies this type.
  build(this: Builder<T, RequiredKeys<T>>): T {
    return (this as any).data as T;
  }
}

// Usage
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  age?: number;
}

const user = new Builder<User>()
  .set('id', '123')
  .set('name', 'John')
  .set('email', 'john@example.com')
  .build();

// new Builder<User>().set('name', 'John').build();
// Error: Builder<User, "name"> not assignable to Builder<User, RequiredKeys<User>>

description.en:
Implement TypeScript's built-in `Pick<T, K>` and `Omit<T, K>` utility types yourself, without referencing the global `Pick`/`Omit`.

**Requirements for Pick:**
- Extract only the specified properties from an object type
- The key parameter must be constrained to `keyof T` so invalid keys are a compile-time error
- Preserve the original modifiers (readonly, optional) of the picked properties

**Requirements for Omit:**
- Exclude the specified properties from an object type
- Unlike Pick, the key parameter is conventionally constrained to `keyof any` (i.e. `string | number | symbol`), not `keyof T` — you should be able to omit a key that doesn't even exist on `T` without an error, matching the standard library's behavior
- Build it in terms of `Pick` and your own `Exclude`, not as an unrelated implementation

**Function signatures:**
typescript
type MyPick<T, K extends keyof T> = {
  [P in K]: T[P];
};

type MyExclude<T, U> = T extends U ? never : T;

type MyOmit<T, K extends keyof any> = MyPick<T, MyExclude<keyof T, K>>;


**Example:**
typescript
interface User {
  readonly id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  age?: number;
}

type UserPreview = MyPick<User, 'name' | 'email'>;
// { name: string; email: string }

type UserWithoutEmail = MyOmit<User, 'email'>;
// { readonly id: number; name: string; age?: number }

// MyOmit<User, 'email' | 'nonExistentKey'> // still compiles - Omit's K is keyof any, not keyof T
// MyPick<User, 'nonExistentKey'> // Error - Pick's K is constrained to keyof T


**Edge cases:**
- Picking/omitting a `readonly` or optional property must preserve that modifier on the result
- `MyPick<T, never>` and `MyOmit<T, keyof T>` should both produce `{}`
- `MyOmit` should accept a key union that doesn't exist on `T` at all (this is standard library behavior, unlike Pick)
- Picking or omitting a union of multiple keys at once

